<h2 class="section"> 5.11 Previewing Models (<code>viewmesh</code>) </h2>

<p>Viewmesh is a tool included with Crystal Space that can be used to
preview models (mesh factories and libraries).
</p>
<a name="1"></a>
<h3 class="subheading"> Commandline Options </h3>

<ul>
<li> <samp>&lsquo;-R&rsquo;</samp>
Real path from where to load the model. This option takes a path and
then mounts it to <samp>&lsquo;/tmp/viewmesh&rsquo;</samp>. Then it sets the current
<small>VFS</small> directory to that.
</li><li> <samp>&lsquo;-C&rsquo;</samp>
This is the current <small>VFS</small> directory to use when loading the model.
If you use this option in combination with <samp>&lsquo;-R&rsquo;</samp> you can change
the current directory relative to <samp>&lsquo;/tmp/viewmesh&rsquo;</samp>.
</li><li> <samp>&lsquo;-L&rsquo;</samp>
Load a library file (for textures or materials for example). This is a
<small>VFS</small> path to the library file (possibly relative to the current
<small>VFS</small> dir as given by <samp>&lsquo;-R&rsquo;</samp> and <samp>&lsquo;-C&rsquo;</samp>).
</li><li> <samp>&lsquo;-Scale&rsquo;</samp>
Scale the loaded object with the given factor.
</li><li> <samp>&lsquo;-RoomSize&rsquo;</samp>
The model is loaded in a room. With this option you can change the
size of that room. By default the size is 5.
</li><li> <samp>&lsquo;-RenderLoop&rsquo;</samp>
Use another renderloop. By default the standard renderloop is used but you
can also use <samp>&lsquo;diffuse&rsquo;</samp> or <samp>&lsquo;shadowed&rsquo;</samp>.
</li></ul>

<p>And then there is an optional filename parameter. Here is an example on how
to use viewmesh:
</p>
<table><tr><td>&nbsp;</td><td><pre class="example">viewmesh -R=c:\data\gamedata.zip -C=objects/actor factories/genActor
</pre></td></tr></table>
<p>This example requires some explanation. First we use the <samp>&lsquo;-R&rsquo;</samp> option
to take our game data archive and mount that to <samp>&lsquo;/tmp/viewmesh&rsquo;</samp>.
Then we use the <samp>&lsquo;-C&rsquo;</samp> option to go inside the <samp>&lsquo;objects/actor&rsquo;</samp>
directory that is inside that <small>ZIP</small> archive. And finally we load
the actual model that is still in a deeper directory called
<samp>&lsquo;factories/genActor&rsquo;</samp>. This example demonstrates how it can be useful
to have good control over the current directory in <small>VFS</small>. Usually
with models exported from blender2crystal there will be a <samp>&lsquo;factories&rsquo;</samp>
and a <samp>&lsquo;textures&rsquo;</samp> directory. So you want the current directory to be
the parent of those so that the model can reference textures like
<samp>&lsquo;textures/bla.jpg&rsquo;</samp>.
</p>
